export const QUESTIONS = {"office_professional":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your current office layout look like — are you in a leased space you've been in for a while, or are you actively thinking about a renovation, buildout, or relocation in the next year or two?","goodResponse":"Office environments have a real impact on client perception and employee retention for professional services firms. Understanding where you are in the lifecycle of your current space helps me see where we might be a fit. When was the space last updated?","badResponse":"We do commercial office buildouts and renovations for professional service firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are there things about your current space that are working against you — acoustics in conference rooms, inadequate private offices for client calls, or a reception area that doesn't match the level of your firm?","goodResponse":"Client-facing spaces communicate your firm's quality before anyone says a word. A conference room that's acoustically uncomfortable or a lobby that feels dated sends a message to prospects and clients. What's the biggest physical limitation of your current space?","badResponse":"We fix those exact pain points in professional service office buildouts.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your office space is creating friction — whether it's client perceptions during meetings, staff discomfort, or an environment that doesn't reflect what you charge — how does that affect your ability to win and retain high-value clients or top talent?","goodResponse":"Professional service firms compete on trust and perceived quality. The physical environment is part of that signal. A firm that charges premium fees but operates out of a tired office creates cognitive dissonance for clients. That gap has a real cost.","badResponse":"Your space affects your brand. We can upgrade it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your office space was designed to match the level of your firm — with proper acoustics, a professional reception area, and private offices that work for client meetings — how would that change the way clients experience your firm from the moment they walk in?","goodResponse":"That's the shift we see every time — a space that matches the firm's reputation reinforces everything else you do. Let me walk you through what a professional services office renovation project looks like from planning to completion.","badResponse":"We build professional office environments. Let's start with a walkthrough of your current space.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you're planning to expand your team in the next year — adding headcount, conference rooms, or support space — has the physical buildout planning been part of that conversation, or is it something you'll figure out when you get there?","goodResponse":"Headcount growth and physical space constraints are something a lot of professional service firms manage reactively — they hire first and then discover they've run out of offices. Planning the buildout now saves time and disruption later. What's your growth trajectory looking like?","badResponse":"We help professional service firms plan space expansions that stay ahead of their headcount growth.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had situations where rapid growth left you with staff working in makeshift spaces, sharing offices, or using conference rooms as overflow workspace — creating a professional environment that didn't match your firm's reputation?","goodResponse":"Makeshift office arrangements are a productivity and culture problem as much as a space problem. Clients notice when staff are working in awkward conditions, and top hires notice it too. How long did that situation persist before you could address it?","badResponse":"We plan office expansions that keep your environment professional through growth.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If space constraints are causing you to defer hiring, limit client meeting capacity, or create an environment that talented candidates judge negatively during onsite interviews — what does that do to your growth trajectory and competitive positioning?","goodResponse":"Talent competition is real in professional services, and office environment is now a factor in candidate decisions. If your space is a liability in the hiring process, it's costing you talent. That compounding effect on growth is worth addressing proactively.","badResponse":"Space constraints limit your growth. Let's plan around your hiring roadmap.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your space was built out ahead of your hiring plan — so that new offices, collaboration areas, and client-facing rooms were ready when you needed them rather than six months after — how would that change your ability to hire and onboard talent smoothly?","goodResponse":"Proactive buildout means your environment is always professional, and new hires walk into a space that signals the firm they joined is organized and well-run. Let me walk you through how we plan and execute a phased office expansion.","badResponse":"We do phased office expansions for growing professional service firms. Let's map your hiring plan.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"What's the condition of your building's core infrastructure — HVAC, electrical capacity, data cabling — and has any of it become a limiting factor for how you operate or how you use the space?","goodResponse":"Older commercial spaces often have infrastructure limitations that weren't designed for modern office density or technology loads. HVAC capacity issues, outdated electrical panels, and inadequate data infrastructure are common in spaces that were built before the late 1990s. What's been the most noticeable infrastructure limitation in your space?","badResponse":"We assess and upgrade commercial building infrastructure as part of office renovation projects.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had HVAC failures, power quality issues, or network infrastructure bottlenecks that disrupted operations — or required reactive maintenance calls that cost more than a planned upgrade would have?","goodResponse":"Reactive infrastructure maintenance is almost always more expensive than a planned capital improvement, and the downtime it creates during a repair is a real operational cost. How significant was the last infrastructure issue you dealt with?","badResponse":"We do planned infrastructure upgrades that prevent costly reactive repairs.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If aging building infrastructure caused a significant operational disruption during a critical client deadline or presentation — and you had to explain the situation to a client — what's the reputational cost of that on top of the direct repair expense?","goodResponse":"Professional service firms are selling reliability and competence. An infrastructure failure during a client-critical moment undercuts that message. The cost of the conversation with that client often exceeds the cost of the repair.","badResponse":"Infrastructure failures at critical moments are expensive in more ways than one.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your office infrastructure — HVAC, electrical, and structured cabling — was assessed and upgraded to match your current and future operational needs, how would that change your confidence in the reliability of your work environment?","goodResponse":"An infrastructure investment that eliminates reactive maintenance and operational surprises has a clear ROI. Let me walk you through what a commercial infrastructure assessment and upgrade project looks like for a space your size.","badResponse":"We do commercial infrastructure assessments and upgrades. Let's start with a walkthrough.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"tech_company":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"Where is your team working right now — are you in a leased office, a co-working space, or is there a hybrid model where you're thinking about what the permanent footprint should look like?","goodResponse":"Tech companies are at a real inflection point with their real estate decisions — co-working is flexible but expensive at scale, and long-term leases require confidence in headcount projections. Understanding where you are in that decision helps me see where we'd be a fit. What's driving the current setup?","badResponse":"We do commercial office buildouts and tenant improvements for tech companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Is the current space creating friction for your team — whether it's poor acoustics for deep work, video call environments that look unprofessional, or a layout that doesn't support the way engineering and product teams actually collaborate?","goodResponse":"Tech office design has some specific requirements that generic commercial spaces don't address — whiteboard walls, acoustic separation between focus and collaboration zones, and AV infrastructure that actually works. What are the biggest physical pain points your team complains about?","badResponse":"We design tech-specific office environments that support how engineering teams work.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your office environment is making it harder to recruit top-tier engineers — because candidates compare it unfavorably to competitors with purpose-built spaces — what's the downstream cost in hiring timeline and offer competitiveness?","goodResponse":"In a tight engineering talent market, office environment is a real factor. A space that feels like an afterthought signals to candidates how the company operates. If you're losing even one senior engineer to a competitor with a better space, the cost of that hire is substantial.","badResponse":"Poor office environments hurt recruiting. Purpose-built spaces help.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your office was designed around how your engineering and product teams actually work — with proper collaboration zones, focus areas, and AV infrastructure that supports your remote-hybrid model — how would that change team productivity and your recruiting story?","goodResponse":"The right office environment becomes a recruiting and retention asset. Let me walk you through what a tech office buildout looks like and how we approach the design-to-build process.","badResponse":"We build tech-specific office environments. Let's start with a space planning conversation.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have a server room or on-premise infrastructure room in your office — and if so, is the mechanical and electrical buildout of that space adequate for your current power and cooling requirements?","goodResponse":"Even primarily cloud-based tech companies often have edge infrastructure, networking equipment, or on-prem backup systems that require properly conditioned space. Inadequate power and cooling in those areas creates both operational risk and hardware longevity issues. What does your current infrastructure room look like?","badResponse":"We build and upgrade server room and infrastructure spaces for tech companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you experienced hardware failures, overheating events, or cooling system issues in your server or network room — or found that your power capacity isn't keeping up with the density of equipment you've added over time?","goodResponse":"Hardware failures from thermal events are extremely expensive — both in equipment replacement and in the downtime they cause. And they're almost always preceded by warning signs that the infrastructure wasn't scaling with the equipment load. What's been the most significant infrastructure issue in that space?","badResponse":"We address the power and cooling gaps that lead to hardware failures before they happen.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a cooling failure in your network room took down your core infrastructure during a critical sprint or a customer-facing incident — and the SLA clock was running — what's the operational and reputational cost of that downtime?","goodResponse":"For a software company, infrastructure downtime during a customer-facing incident has direct contract and SLA implications. The cost of a properly built infrastructure room is typically recovered in preventing a single significant downtime event.","badResponse":"Infrastructure downtime is expensive for tech companies. Proper buildout prevents it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your infrastructure room had proper power distribution, redundant cooling, and structured cabling that matched your actual equipment density — how would that change your team's confidence in the reliability of your on-prem systems?","goodResponse":"Properly built infrastructure rooms are a foundation for operational confidence. Let me walk you through what a server room assessment and upgrade project looks like and what we typically find.","badResponse":"We build and upgrade infrastructure rooms for tech companies. Let's assess your current setup.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you planning to expand your footprint — taking on additional floors, building out a new location, or doing a significant renovation — and if so, is the construction planning happening in parallel with your product and hiring roadmap?","goodResponse":"Tech company growth phases often create misalignment between the hiring plan and the physical space plan. Companies end up in cramped conditions or signing leases for space they can't fill yet. How synchronized is your headcount plan with your current space capacity?","badResponse":"We help tech companies plan office expansions that align with their growth stages.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Has space become a constraint on your hiring or team organization — are you putting product and engineering teams in layouts that don't support how they actually work together because you ran out of options in your current floor plan?","goodResponse":"Physical space constraints that force suboptimal team layouts are a real productivity and culture problem. Engineering teams that can't sit together or collaborate physically because of space fragmentation see measurable velocity impacts. What does your current floor plan look like?","badResponse":"We design office expansions that fix team layout constraints before they become culture problems.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If space constraints are creating team friction, slowing onboarding, or forcing you to defer headcount — and that's starting to affect sprint velocity or product delivery — what does that mean for your roadmap commitments to customers or investors?","goodResponse":"Execution velocity at the team level is directly tied to how well the physical environment supports collaboration. If cramped or poorly organized spaces are costing you sprint points, the business impact is real. The math on a buildout investment versus productivity loss is often compelling.","badResponse":"Space constraints affect delivery velocity. Let's solve that proactively.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your office expansion was built around your engineering and product team structure — with the right collaboration zones, quiet focus areas, and room to grow for two to three years — how would that change your ability to execute your roadmap and scale the team?","goodResponse":"The right space investment pays dividends in execution velocity and recruiting for years. Let me walk you through how we approach tech office expansion projects and what the planning process looks like.","badResponse":"We build tech-tailored office expansions. Let's start with a planning session.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"healthcare":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your current clinical space look like — how many operatories or treatment rooms do you have, and is the physical layout still matching the way your practice operates today compared to when the space was originally built out?","goodResponse":"Healthcare practices often grow their patient volume and service mix without updating the physical infrastructure to match. The operatory count, sterilization room placement, and patient flow design that worked five years ago may be creating friction today. When was your space last renovated?","badResponse":"We specialize in healthcare facility buildouts and renovations — dental, medical, and specialty practices.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Is your current layout creating patient flow problems — long waits in small reception areas, sterilization bottlenecks that slow your providers, or treatment rooms that don't have the utility infrastructure for the equipment you're running?","goodResponse":"Patient throughput in healthcare is directly constrained by the physical environment. Sterilization room bottlenecks alone can reduce daily procedure capacity by 15 to 20 percent in dental practices. What's the most limiting physical constraint in your practice right now?","badResponse":"We redesign healthcare spaces to eliminate the flow bottlenecks that limit patient capacity.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If physical space limitations are capping your daily patient capacity — meaning you're turning away patients or extending wait times because the space can't support more throughput — what does that cost you in monthly collections and in patient retention?","goodResponse":"In most healthcare practices, a single additional operatory or treatment room generates enough additional revenue in the first year to cover the cost of the renovation. The capacity constraint is a direct revenue ceiling. What's your current wait time for new patient appointments?","badResponse":"Capacity constraints are revenue constraints. The right buildout solves both.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If we designed a renovation that added operatory capacity, optimized your patient flow, and brought your utility infrastructure up to support your current and planned equipment — what would that do to your monthly patient volume and revenue in the first year?","goodResponse":"The ROI calculation for healthcare renovations is usually very clear. Let me walk you through what a healthcare facility buildout project looks like from design through occupancy, and what the typical timeline and investment range is.","badResponse":"We build healthcare-specific renovations with fast ROI. Let's walk your space.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you thinking about opening a new location — a satellite office, a second practice, or a new market — and if so, is the site selection and construction planning happening yet, or are you still in the concept stage?","goodResponse":"Healthcare multi-site expansion requires a very different planning process than other commercial buildouts, particularly around state and local regulatory requirements, ADA compliance, and clinical infrastructure. Understanding where you are in that process helps me see where we'd be most useful. What's driving the expansion thinking?","badResponse":"We build healthcare facilities for multi-site expansion — from site selection through certificate of occupancy.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a previous buildout or renovation that ran significantly over budget, over timeline, or had compliance issues with your local health department or building inspector — that delayed your opening and cost you revenue?","goodResponse":"Healthcare buildout delays are extremely expensive — you're carrying lease costs, equipment financing, and staff payroll while the revenue clock hasn't started. And regulatory inspection failures can extend a delay by weeks or months. What happened with the situation you're thinking of?","badResponse":"We deliver healthcare buildouts on time and through the regulatory process with fewer surprises.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a new location opening is delayed by three months due to construction or permitting issues — and you're already paying lease, equipment, and staff costs — what does that do to your first-year breakeven timeline for that location?","goodResponse":"Every month of delay in a healthcare facility opening extends the breakeven point by more than a month, because you're carrying full fixed costs without any revenue offset. That's a calculation that makes the case for working with contractors who understand the healthcare regulatory environment.","badResponse":"Opening delays are expensive. We minimize them in healthcare buildouts.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your new location was built by a contractor who knew healthcare regulatory requirements, managed the inspection process proactively, and delivered on the timeline your financial projections were built around — how would that change your confidence in the expansion decision?","goodResponse":"That confidence comes from working with a contractor who's done this before in healthcare. Let me walk you through our healthcare buildout process and the typical timeline from permit to certificate of occupancy.","badResponse":"We specialize in healthcare buildouts and know the regulatory process. Let's walk your site.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"When was the last time your HVAC, plumbing, or electrical systems in your clinical space were assessed or upgraded — specifically for the load and air exchange requirements of a healthcare facility?","goodResponse":"Healthcare HVAC requirements — particularly air exchange rates and pressure differentials in clinical areas — are more demanding than standard commercial HVAC, and systems that aren't maintained or upgraded to those standards create both regulatory and patient safety issues. What's the age of your current mechanical systems?","badResponse":"We assess and upgrade mechanical systems in healthcare facilities to meet clinical-grade standards.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had HVAC performance issues in clinical areas — temperature control problems, air quality complaints from staff or patients, or a state health inspection that flagged mechanical system deficiencies?","goodResponse":"Healthcare facility inspections that flag mechanical deficiencies can result in corrective action requirements, and patient-facing air quality issues affect both safety and patient satisfaction scores. What was the most significant HVAC issue your facility has dealt with?","badResponse":"We fix mechanical system deficiencies in healthcare facilities before they become inspection findings.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a state health inspection found that your HVAC system wasn't meeting clinical air exchange requirements and issued a corrective action order — requiring shutdown of affected clinical spaces during remediation — what does that do to your patient schedule and revenue for that period?","goodResponse":"Forced clinical space shutdowns for regulatory deficiencies are extremely disruptive — you're rescheduling patients, absorbing the staff cost, and managing the reputational impact. A proactive mechanical assessment is a small fraction of that cost.","badResponse":"Regulatory shutdowns from mechanical deficiencies are expensive. Proactive assessment prevents them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your mechanical systems were assessed, upgraded to current healthcare standards, and documented to pass your next state health inspection — how would that change your confidence in the compliance posture of your facility?","goodResponse":"Clinical mechanical compliance gives you confidence in inspections and protects your patient care environment. Let me walk you through what a healthcare facility mechanical assessment looks like and what we typically find.","badResponse":"We do mechanical assessments and upgrades for healthcare facilities. Let's schedule a walkthrough.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"retail_food":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your current kitchen or service space look like — is it purpose-built for your concept, or are you working around a layout that came with the lease and has always had some limitations?","goodResponse":"Most restaurant and retail food operators work around the existing layout for years until the limitations start costing them real money in efficiency or capacity. Understanding how your space was originally designed versus how you actually use it tells me where the biggest opportunities are. When was the kitchen last touched?","badResponse":"We do commercial kitchen and restaurant buildouts and renovations.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are there bottlenecks in your kitchen workflow — line configuration, equipment placement, or ventilation limitations — that slow ticket times, create staff friction, or cap how many covers you can do during a peak shift?","goodResponse":"Kitchen inefficiency is directly measurable in ticket times and cover counts. A poorly sequenced kitchen line can cost a restaurant 20 to 30 covers per shift, which adds up quickly. What's your current bottleneck during a Friday dinner rush?","badResponse":"We redesign commercial kitchens to eliminate the workflow bottlenecks that limit throughput.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your kitchen bottlenecks are causing you to cap reservations, slow table turns, or put out slower ticket times than your concept requires — what does that do to your revenue per shift and your food cost percentage when waste increases?","goodResponse":"Kitchen efficiency has a direct multiplier effect on both top-line revenue and food cost. A renovation that improves throughput by even 15 percent can have an ROI measured in months, not years, in a busy operation. What's your current average ticket time on a peak night?","badResponse":"Kitchen bottlenecks cost revenue. The renovation ROI is usually fast for busy operations.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your kitchen was redesigned with a workflow-optimized line, properly positioned equipment, and ventilation that met code — so your team could execute your concept at full speed during every peak shift — how would that change your revenue and staff turnover?","goodResponse":"Staff retention improves dramatically when the physical environment supports the work instead of fighting it. Let me walk you through what a commercial kitchen renovation looks like from design through health department approval.","badResponse":"We build kitchens that match your concept and your volume. Let's walk your current layout.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you planning a new location, a second concept, or a buildout for a space you've recently leased — and if so, where are you in the process? Do you have permits, architectural plans, or is it still in the early stages?","goodResponse":"Getting the construction process started right for a food and beverage concept is critical to hitting your opening target. The permitting process for commercial kitchens, specifically the health department approval sequence, has a longer lead time than most operators expect. What's your target opening date?","badResponse":"We build food and beverage concepts from permit to health department approval.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a previous buildout that ran over timeline or budget — or had health department or fire marshal issues at inspection that delayed your opening — and had to push your launch date back while carrying rent and pre-opening costs?","goodResponse":"Health department and fire marshal inspections for commercial kitchens are where most restaurant buildout delays happen, and they almost always trace back to contractors who didn't understand the specific code requirements for food service. What happened with the buildout you're thinking of?","badResponse":"We build food service spaces that pass health department inspections the first time.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your opening is delayed two months while your team is paid and your lease is running — and you opened with less capital than projected because the buildout ran over budget — what does that do to your runway in the first six months of operation?","goodResponse":"Opening capital shortfalls are the leading cause of restaurant closures in the first year. A buildout that runs over budget or schedule doesn't just cost money — it changes the financial trajectory of the entire business from the first day. The contractor choice is a significant variable in that outcome.","badResponse":"Buildout overruns are a capital risk. Better contractors reduce that risk substantially.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your buildout was managed by a contractor who knew the health department requirements, had a realistic and detailed timeline, and had experience delivering food service spaces on budget — how would that change your confidence going into the opening?","goodResponse":"Opening with confidence and capital intact changes everything about how you operate in the first six months. Let me walk you through our process for restaurant and retail food buildouts and what our typical timeline looks like.","badResponse":"We deliver food service buildouts on time and through the health department process. Let's talk about your project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How old is your current dining room or front-of-house design, and is the atmosphere it creates still matching where your brand and price point are today — or has it drifted from where you want it to be?","goodResponse":"Front-of-house design has a direct impact on perceived value, and a dining room that was modern five years ago can feel dated today. The guest experience starts before they order, and the physical environment sets the tone for everything else. When was your front of house last updated?","badResponse":"We renovate front-of-house environments to match evolving brand positioning.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you seen guests comment on the atmosphere negatively in reviews — or noticed that the look and feel of the space is out of step with what your food and price point communicate — and haven't been able to address it yet?","goodResponse":"Review mentions of the physical space are among the most actionable feedback a restaurant can get, because the fix is permanent. A single renovation that brings the space in line with the food quality can measurably shift your star rating and repeat visit rate. What are the most common space-related comments in your reviews?","badResponse":"We bring dining room design in line with the food and price point. It's one of the highest-ROI renovations.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your dining room environment is creating a perception gap — where guests feel the food is worth more than the space suggests, or vice versa — how is that affecting your average check, your review scores, and your repeat customer rate?","goodResponse":"A perception gap between food quality and environment is a real pricing and retention constraint. Guests who feel the space doesn't justify the price point become infrequent visitors. A renovation that closes that gap has a direct and measurable impact on average check and repeat business.","badResponse":"Perception gaps between food and environment hurt check averages and repeat visits.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your dining room renovation matched your food quality and price point — creating an environment guests actively comment on positively and photograph — how would that change your review scores and average weekly covers?","goodResponse":"The viral photography effect of a well-designed dining room is a real marketing asset in today's social media environment. Let me walk you through what a front-of-house renovation project looks like and what we see for typical ROI timelines.","badResponse":"We renovate front-of-house environments for food concepts. Let's walk your space.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"trades_contractor":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have a dedicated shop, office, or facility space — and is the layout and condition of that space set up in a way that actually supports how your crews operate, or is it something that's been outgrown or cobbled together over time?","goodResponse":"Trade and contracting businesses often outgrow their original shop layouts — what worked for a three-person crew doesn't work for a twelve-person operation. Storage, fabrication, equipment maintenance, and office functions end up competing for the same inadequate space. What does your current facility look like?","badResponse":"We build and renovate trade contractor facilities — shops, offices, and equipment storage.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are there efficiency problems in your shop or yard — vehicles and equipment that are hard to access, materials that are poorly organized, or a workflow that creates bottlenecks at the start of every shift when crews are staging for the day?","goodResponse":"Morning staging inefficiency in a trades operation adds up quickly — if your crew spends 30 minutes every morning sorting out equipment and materials because the shop isn't organized to support quick deployment, that's real cost every single day. What's the most frustrating daily inefficiency in your current setup?","badResponse":"We design trade facilities that eliminate staging and storage inefficiencies.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If shop inefficiencies are adding 20 to 30 minutes to crew deployment every morning — across multiple crews, every working day — what does that time cost translate to annually in labor expense and billable hours lost?","goodResponse":"The math on facility inefficiency is straightforward once you run it. Twenty-five minutes per crew per day across a crew of four at $45 an hour is over $15,000 per year in lost productivity from a single inefficiency. That's usually a compelling argument for a facility upgrade.","badResponse":"Facility inefficiency has a real dollar cost. A better layout pays for itself fast.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your shop was designed around how your crews actually work — with organized material storage, clear vehicle access, and a staging area that gets crews out the door efficiently — how would that change your daily operational costs and job capacity?","goodResponse":"The operational ROI on a well-designed trade facility is usually faster than owners expect, because it compounds every single working day. Let me walk you through what a trade contractor facility design-build looks like.","badResponse":"We build trade contractor facilities that improve crew efficiency. Let's walk your current setup.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you work as a subcontractor — do you have an established relationship with two or three general contractors who call you regularly, or are you still working primarily job to job without a consistent pipeline?","goodResponse":"Subcontractor revenue stability is almost entirely determined by GC relationships, and GCs give their best work to subs who they trust and who show up professionally. Understanding where your pipeline comes from tells me what kind of growth conversation we're having.","badResponse":"We help trade contractors establish the facility and professional profile that attracts GC relationships.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever lost a bid or been passed over for a subcontract because your facility, insurance documentation, or professional presentation didn't match the standards of the GC or owner you were pitching?","goodResponse":"GCs pre-qualify subs, and the ones with organized operations — proper shop facilities, professional documentation, and good references — get the call first. The appearance of a well-run operation matters in that pre-qualification. What do you think held you back in the situation you're describing?","badResponse":"We help trade contractors present professionally at the pre-qualification level.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're consistently losing GC relationships or pre-qualification reviews because your operational footprint doesn't look the part — what does that mean for your ability to grow revenue beyond your current ceiling?","goodResponse":"For subcontractors, the pre-qualification perception is the gate to larger and more consistent work. A facility and professional profile that signals a well-run operation opens doors that a DIY appearance keeps closed. The revenue difference between those two categories of subs is substantial.","badResponse":"Pre-qualification perception limits your revenue ceiling. Let's raise it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your facility upgrade positioned you as a professional, well-organized operation that any GC would be proud to have on their list — how would that change the type and volume of subcontract work you could pursue?","goodResponse":"The facility is part of your business card. Let me walk you through what a trade contractor facility upgrade looks like and the typical investment range.","badResponse":"We build the facilities that help trade contractors move up the subcontract tier. Let's talk.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you have proper secure storage for your tools, materials, and equipment — and is that storage organized in a way that lets you track what you have, what's been deployed to a job, and what needs to be replaced or repaired?","goodResponse":"Tool and material inventory management is a significant cost center for trade contractors, and most of that cost comes from disorganized storage. Lost tools, duplicate purchases, and materials that can't be found on short notice are common symptoms of a facility that doesn't have a proper storage system. How do you currently track your tool and material inventory?","badResponse":"We build organized, secure tool and material storage systems for trade contractors.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had situations where tools were lost, stolen, or damaged because they weren't secured properly — or found yourself buying materials you already had because the storage system made it impossible to know what was on hand?","goodResponse":"Tool theft and duplicate material purchases are two of the most common hidden costs in trade contracting, and both trace directly to inadequate storage and organization. What's your best estimate of what tool and material losses cost you last year?","badResponse":"Secure, organized storage prevents tool losses and duplicate purchases. We build it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If tool and material losses, theft, and duplicate purchases are costing you $10,000 or $20,000 per year — in addition to the time your crew spends looking for things that should be instantly accessible — what does that add up to over three to five years of operation?","goodResponse":"The cumulative cost of disorganized storage is one of those line items that trade contractors rarely calculate explicitly, but when they do, it's almost always large enough to justify a significant facility investment. Would it be useful to walk through that estimate for your operation?","badResponse":"Storage inefficiency has a big cumulative cost. A proper system pays for itself fast.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your shop had a properly built-out tool storage and materials management system — with secure racking, clear labeling, and a layout that matched how crews check in and out of the shop — how would that change your daily operational efficiency and annual materials cost?","goodResponse":"The right storage system reduces losses, eliminates duplicate purchases, and cuts the time crews spend staging and unstaging. Let me walk you through what we build for trade contractors and what the typical investment and payback period looks like.","badResponse":"We build trade contractor storage systems. The payback period is usually under two years.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"auto_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your shop floor layout look like right now — how many bays do you have, and is the configuration set up to move vehicles efficiently through intake, service, and delivery, or have you outgrown the original design?","goodResponse":"Auto shop layouts have a direct impact on throughput, and a bay configuration that works for a small operation creates serious bottlenecks when volume grows. Lift placement, vehicle staging lanes, and alignment bay positioning all affect how many cars you can turn per day. When was your shop last reconfigured?","badResponse":"We design and build auto service facilities — bay layouts, lifts, alignment equipment, and shop infrastructure.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are there bottlenecks in your shop flow — vehicles blocking each other, service bays that can't be used simultaneously, or a parking situation that's creating friction at drop-off and pickup times?","goodResponse":"Vehicle staging and bay access bottlenecks are the most common throughput limiters in auto service shops, and they're almost always architectural problems rather than operational ones. A vehicle that blocks two other vehicles from moving costs you time on every shift. What does your most frustrating daily bottleneck look like?","badResponse":"We redesign auto shop layouts to eliminate the flow bottlenecks that cap your throughput.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If bay configuration and vehicle staging issues are limiting you to 70 or 80 percent of your theoretical daily vehicle capacity — and you're turning away same-day appointments because you're full on paper but not in practice — what does that lost throughput cost you monthly?","goodResponse":"Lost throughput in an auto service operation is very measurable. If your average repair order is $400 and you're losing three cars a day to staging bottlenecks, that's $1,200 per day or roughly $25,000 per month. That math usually makes the case for a facility investment pretty quickly.","badResponse":"Lost throughput from layout problems is expensive. Let's calculate yours.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your shop was reconfigured for optimal vehicle flow — with clear staging lanes, properly positioned lifts, and a bay layout that let your technicians work without blocking each other — how many additional vehicles per day could your team service with your current headcount?","goodResponse":"The ROI on an auto shop renovation is usually very calculable before we start, and it's almost always positive within the first year. Let me walk you through what a shop floor reconfiguration looks like and what we'd assess in a walkthrough.","badResponse":"We build and reconfigure auto service facilities for maximum throughput. Let's walk your shop.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you operate a dealership — what does your showroom and customer experience environment look like, and is it positioned to compete with the newer-format dealership experiences that customers are comparing you to when they walk in?","goodResponse":"Dealership showroom design has shifted significantly in the last five years — the open floor plans, the digital display integrations, and the customer lounge expectations have all moved. A showroom that was standard practice in 2015 can feel dated against a newly remodeled competitor. When was your facility last renovated?","badResponse":"We renovate dealership facilities — showrooms, service drives, and customer experience spaces.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you noticed customers commenting on the facility experience — either in CSI scores, online reviews, or directly in conversations — in ways that suggest the physical environment is working against your customer satisfaction scores?","goodResponse":"CSI scores and online reviews that reference the facility experience are a direct signal that the physical environment is affecting your brand. Manufacturer CSI requirements are also becoming more stringent about facility standards. What are you seeing in your review comments or CSI data?","badResponse":"Facility-related CSI impacts are fixable. We renovate dealerships to improve those scores.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your CSI scores are below your manufacturer benchmark because of facility-related comments — and that's affecting your bonus allocation or your standing with the manufacturer for inventory allocation — what's the financial impact of that gap?","goodResponse":"Manufacturer CSI bonuses and inventory allocation advantages for high-CSI dealers can be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars annually. A facility renovation that moves the needle on CSI scores can have a very clear and measurable ROI for a dealership.","badResponse":"CSI impacts affect manufacturer bonuses and inventory allocation. Let's fix the root cause.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your showroom and service drive were renovated to meet current manufacturer standards and modern customer experience expectations — improving your CSI scores and the overall perception of your dealership — how would that change your manufacturer relationship and your competitive position against nearby stores?","goodResponse":"A modern, well-executed facility renovation is one of the few investments that improves both customer satisfaction scores and competitive perception simultaneously. Let me walk you through what a dealership renovation project looks like.","badResponse":"We renovate dealership facilities to improve CSI and competitive standing. Let's scope your project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Is your service drive set up to handle your current volume of daily check-ins efficiently — do customers have a smooth intake experience, or is there congestion, unclear queuing, and wait times that start the service experience on a negative note?","goodResponse":"Service drive experience is where the customer relationship is made or broken in auto service. A congested or disorganized intake process that causes 15 minutes of frustration before the service starts affects CSI scores and return visits regardless of how good the actual service is. What's the most common complaint about the intake process?","badResponse":"We design service drives and intake environments that start the customer experience positively.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"During your morning rush — when multiple customers are dropping off at the same time — does the physical layout of your service drive create confusion, delays, or situations where advisors are running between vehicles instead of managing the experience?","goodResponse":"Morning service drive congestion is the most visible operational problem in auto service, and customers notice it. An advisor who's managing three simultaneous drop-offs in a poorly laid-out drive is giving everyone a worse experience than the same advisor in a well-designed drive with clear queuing. What happens in your drive at 8am on a Tuesday?","badResponse":"We redesign service drives to handle peak morning volume cleanly.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If service drive congestion is creating a poor first impression that shows up in your CSI scores and online reviews — and customers are choosing the dealer down the street partly because their intake process is smoother — what does that mean for your monthly service revenue and customer retention?","goodResponse":"In a competitive service market, intake experience is a real differentiator. Customers who have a smooth drop-off experience are measurably more likely to return and more likely to leave positive reviews. The service drive is your first impression every single visit.","badResponse":"Poor intake experiences affect retention and reviews. Better service drive design fixes it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your service drive was redesigned with clear queuing lanes, a covered advisor station, and a flow that handled your peak morning volume without congestion — how would that change your CSI scores and the return rate of your service customers?","goodResponse":"A well-designed service drive is a competitive advantage that compounds visit after visit. Let me walk you through what a service drive renovation looks like and what we typically deliver for customer satisfaction impact.","badResponse":"We design and build service drives for auto service operations. Let's walk yours.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"financial_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does your branch or advisory office look like from a client-facing environment perspective — is it designed to communicate security, trust, and professionalism in the way a financial services environment should?","goodResponse":"The physical environment of a financial services office sends a strong signal to clients about the institution's stability and professionalism. A tired or dated office creates cognitive dissonance when clients are trusting you with their money. When was your space last renovated?","badResponse":"We build financial services office environments that communicate trust and professionalism.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you noticed prospects or clients making comments about your office environment — or sensed that the physical space is working against the impression you're trying to make when you bring in a high-net-worth client?","goodResponse":"High-net-worth clients in financial services have very calibrated expectations about their advisor's environment. A space that feels inadequate for the conversation you're trying to have is a trust signal in the wrong direction. Has this come up explicitly or do you just sense it?","badResponse":"We build the kind of environment that reinforces client trust in financial services.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your office environment is creating doubt in the minds of high-value prospects — and contributing to a lower close rate on new AUM or insurance relationships than your capabilities warrant — what does that mean for your revenue growth over the next two years?","goodResponse":"In financial services, trust is the product. The office environment is part of how that trust is established. If your physical space is even a small factor in losing one $2 million AUM relationship per year, the renovation ROI calculation is very compelling.","badResponse":"Trust is your product. Your office should reinforce it, not undermine it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your office communicated the stability, professionalism, and attention to detail that your clients expect — with a space that matched your brand and made every client meeting feel like a premium experience — how would that change your close rate on new relationships?","goodResponse":"The right office environment reinforces everything else you do in financial services. Let me walk you through what a financial services office renovation looks like and what we've delivered for similar firms.","badResponse":"We build financial services office environments. Let's start with a walkthrough.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you planning to open a new branch, satellite office, or advisory location — and if so, is the buildout planning happening now, or is that still something you're working toward?","goodResponse":"Financial services branch buildouts have some specific requirements — vault or secure storage, safety and security infrastructure, ADA compliance, and sometimes specific regulatory requirements around record retention space. Understanding where you are in the planning process tells me where we'd be most useful.","badResponse":"We build financial services branch and advisory office locations.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a previous buildout that ran over schedule or budget, or had issues with security system installation, vault construction, or building permits that delayed your opening?","goodResponse":"Financial services buildouts have specific security, vault, and regulatory infrastructure requirements that contractors without that experience often underestimate. Opening delays for a branch are particularly costly because you're paying rent, staff, and overhead before any revenue starts. What happened with the situation you're thinking of?","badResponse":"We build financial services facilities with the specific security and infrastructure requirements in mind.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your branch opening was delayed two months while full pre-opening costs were running — and the delay was caused by a contractor who didn't understand the security or vault requirements — what does that do to your first-year profitability projections for that location?","goodResponse":"Opening delays in financial services are particularly expensive because the cost structure — staffing, security monitoring, lease — is essentially fixed from day one. Two months of delay without revenue is a significant hole in the first-year P&L. The contractor choice is a real variable in that outcome.","badResponse":"Opening delays are expensive in financial services. The right contractor prevents them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your branch buildout was managed by a contractor who understood financial services facility requirements — delivering the security infrastructure, vault, and regulatory-compliant layout on time and on budget — how would that change your expansion confidence?","goodResponse":"The ability to open new locations on schedule and on budget is what enables systematic branch expansion. Let me walk you through our financial services buildout process and what the typical timeline looks like.","badResponse":"We build financial services facilities from permit to opening day. Let's scope your project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"What does the physical security infrastructure of your location look like — are your access control, surveillance, and secure document storage systems current, or is that something that's been on the list to upgrade for a while?","goodResponse":"Physical security requirements for financial services locations have become more stringent from both a regulatory and insurance standpoint. Outdated surveillance, access control gaps, and inadequate secure storage can create both regulatory and claims issues. When were your physical security systems last assessed?","badResponse":"We assess and upgrade physical security infrastructure for financial services locations.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a physical security incident, an insurance claim, or a regulatory review that identified gaps in your access control, surveillance coverage, or secure document storage?","goodResponse":"Physical security gaps in financial services locations show up in insurance premiums, regulatory findings, and occasionally in loss events. Any of those three outcomes is expensive. What was the most significant physical security issue you've dealt with?","badResponse":"We identify and close physical security gaps in financial services locations.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a physical security gap resulted in a loss event or a regulatory finding that triggered higher insurance premiums and a corrective action requirement — what does that do to your operating cost structure and your regulatory standing?","goodResponse":"Physical security incidents and regulatory findings around facility security can affect both your insurance rates and your regulatory examination results. The cost of proactive infrastructure assessment and upgrade is usually a small fraction of either of those outcomes.","badResponse":"Physical security gaps have compounding costs. Proactive upgrades prevent them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your physical security infrastructure — access control, surveillance, secure storage — was assessed, upgraded to current standards, and documented for regulatory and insurance purposes, how would that change your risk posture and your insurance cost?","goodResponse":"Documented, current physical security infrastructure is an insurance and regulatory asset. Let me walk you through what a physical security assessment and upgrade project looks like for a financial services location.","badResponse":"We assess and upgrade physical security infrastructure for financial services. Let's schedule a walkthrough.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"real_estate":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you develop or rehab investment properties — and if so, what does your current project pipeline look like? Are you doing the GC work in-house, using subs you manage yourself, or working with a general contractor for the whole project?","goodResponse":"Real estate investors and developers who manage their own GC work often find that construction management absorbs time that would be more profitably spent on deal sourcing and capital allocation. Understanding how your construction process is organized tells me where we'd add the most value.","badResponse":"We GC residential and commercial investment property rehabs and new builds for real estate developers.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had rehab or development projects run significantly over budget or timeline — cost overruns that eroded your projected margin, or delays that extended your carry costs beyond what the deal penciled at?","goodResponse":"Construction overruns are one of the most common ways real estate investment deals underperform relative to projections. And carry cost extensions from timeline delays compound that problem. What did the gap between projected and actual construction cost look like on your last project that ran over?","badResponse":"We deliver rehabs and developments on budget and schedule. Overruns are the exception, not the rule.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If construction overruns or timeline extensions are reducing your projected cash-on-cash return by three to five percent per project — across a portfolio of two to four projects per year — what does that add up to annually in returns you're leaving on the table?","goodResponse":"Construction performance is a direct lever on investment returns, and it's one of the most controllable variables in a real estate investment business. The difference between a GC who executes on budget and one who doesn't can be the difference between a profitable year and a flat one.","badResponse":"Construction performance directly affects your returns. Consistent execution matters.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a GC relationship that consistently delivered your rehabs and developments on time and within five percent of budget — freeing you to focus on acquisitions and capital instead of managing subs — how would that change your deal velocity and annual return profile?","goodResponse":"The right GC relationship is a growth multiplier for a real estate investment business. Let me walk you through how we structure our relationships with real estate investors and developers and what our process looks like.","badResponse":"We GC real estate investment projects reliably. Let's talk about your current pipeline.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you manage commercial properties — do you have a trusted contractor relationship for tenant improvements and capital projects, or is each project an exercise in finding vendors you've never worked with before?","goodResponse":"Property managers who lack reliable contractor relationships end up with inconsistent quality, unpredictable timelines, and the overhead of re-qualifying vendors for every project. That's a significant operational inefficiency. How are you currently handling tenant improvement and maintenance contractor relationships?","badResponse":"We build ongoing contractor relationships with commercial property managers for TIs and capital projects.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had tenant improvement projects that ran over timeline or budget, created tenant friction during construction, or came back with warranty or defect issues that required return trips and additional cost?","goodResponse":"Tenant improvement quality and timeline is a direct factor in tenant satisfaction and retention. A TI that runs over schedule or delivers defect issues affects the tenant relationship from the first day in their new space. What's the most problematic TI project you've managed?","badResponse":"We deliver tenant improvements on time and with minimal tenant disruption. That's our standard.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If poor TI execution is contributing to tenant friction, reduced renewal rates, or reputational issues with your building that make it harder to attract new tenants — what does that do to your occupancy rate and the valuation of your portfolio?","goodResponse":"Tenant retention rates have a direct mathematical relationship to building valuation through their effect on NOI stability. A property manager with a reputation for smooth tenant improvements and responsive maintenance is a competitive advantage at every lease renewal.","badResponse":"TI quality affects occupancy and valuation. Reliable construction partnerships improve both.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a construction partner you could call for every TI and capital project — who knew your buildings, delivered on schedule, and resolved issues without friction — how would that change your operating efficiency and your tenant satisfaction scores?","goodResponse":"A reliable construction partner changes the entire operational dynamic for property management. Let me walk you through how we structure ongoing relationships with commercial property managers and what that looks like in practice.","badResponse":"We build ongoing contractor relationships with property managers. Let's discuss your portfolio.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you're a developer working on ground-up residential or commercial projects — where are you currently in your pipeline, and do you have a GC relationship in place for your next project, or are you going back out to bid?","goodResponse":"Development projects benefit significantly from having an established GC relationship with a firm that understands your design and quality standards. Going out to bid on every project creates variability in execution quality and timeline predictability. What's your current approach to GC selection?","badResponse":"We build ground-up residential and commercial development projects for established developers.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a development project where the GC you selected underperformed — missed schedule milestones, had quality control issues that required rework, or had communication problems that left you unable to give accurate updates to your investors?","goodResponse":"GC underperformance on a development project is one of the most stressful situations a developer faces — you're caught between your investors and your contractor, and every week of delay affects your proforma. What happened with the situation you're describing?","badResponse":"We deliver development projects with the communication and quality control that keeps investors informed.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a GC who underdelivered caused your project to run four to six months over schedule — extending your construction loan period, triggering investor inquiries, and reducing your projected IRR — what does that do to your ability to raise capital for the next deal?","goodResponse":"A development deal that misses projections significantly affects your track record with investors, and your track record is your primary fundraising asset. The right GC choice is a capital markets decision, not just a construction decision.","badResponse":"GC performance affects your investor track record. That has real capital-raising implications.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a GC relationship with a firm that had a track record of delivering ground-up projects on schedule, on budget, and with the quality control to keep your investor reporting clean — how would that change your confidence going into your next capital raise?","goodResponse":"The right GC is part of your investment thesis. Let me walk you through our development project process and what our track record looks like across comparable projects.","badResponse":"We GC ground-up development projects for serious developers. Let's talk about your next project.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]]};
